Abstract:
In this project, we extended a pathtracer implemented in homework 3 to render realistic
soap bubbles. Our technical approach involved modifying the bsdf class to include
Wards BRDF for simulating light reflections off microfacet surfaces. We utilized Nigel
Morriss approach from "Capturing the Reflectance Model of Soap Bubbles" to achieve
this effect accurately. Our implementation involved creating a new .dae file for
rendering, editing parse_material function, and implementing the WardBSDF class with
reflectance color and roughness parameters. Challenges included understanding and
implementing the complex BSDF formulas and debugging issues related to integrating
the WardBSDF class with the rest of the rendering pipeline. Ultimately, we were able to
visualize iridescent effects on spheres. Through this project, we gained insights into
mathematical and physics principles related to Wards BRDF, improved teamwork, and
debugging skills, and identified areas for future improvement in time management and
integration techniques for more complex rendering effects.
Technical Approach:
For our project, we extended the pathtracer we implemented in Homework 3 in order to
begin rendering realistic soap bubbles. We first modified the bsdf class to include an
implementation of Wards BRDF as suggested in Nigel Morriss approach in Capturing
the Reflectance Model of Soap Bubbles. To implement the specific function used the
equation outlined in Bruce Walters Notes on the Ward BRDF, which allows us to
simulate light being reflected off of surfaces composed of microfacets. We used Wards
BRDF because it is more accurate than the Phong model in that it captures how light is
reflected off a surface from any direction.
We then created a new .dae file for the Ward BRDF to be rendered correctly and
modified the parse_material function to correctly apply the material within the scene.
We have initialized the WardBSDF class with a reflectance color and two roughness
parameters ax and ay. The reflectance color represents the color of the material, and
the roughness parameters control the spread of the reflection in the x and y directions.
We then implemented the f function to calculate the BSDF value for given incoming and
outgoing directions. It first checks if the directions are in the same hemisphere as the
normal. If they are not, it returns a zero BSDF value. Then it calculates the half-vector
and checks if it's in the same hemisphere as the normal. If it's not, it again returns a
zero BSDF value. Finally, it calculates the BSDF value using the Ward model and
returns it. We also implemented the sample_f function. On a high level, it generates a
sample in the incoming direction, given the outgoing direction and randomly generated
values. Additionally it calculates the BSDF value and PDF for the sample. Specifically, it
first generates a sample in the half-vector domain using the anisotropic Gaussian
distribution defined by the roughness parameters. Then it reflects the outgoing direction
about the half-vector to get the incoming direction. If the incoming direction is not in the
same hemisphere as the normal, it sets the PDF to 0 and returns a zero BSDF value.
Finally, it calculates the PDF and BSDF value for the sample and returns the BSDF
value.

Difficulty:
We initially struggled with the BSDF implementation. Since none of us are familiar with
the iridescent effect, it took us a while to study the formula from Notes on the Ward
BRDF by Bruce Walter and convert the mathematical formula into the algorithm. And
we spent a lot of time trying to figure out the logical connection between the dae file and
the actual program. In the beginning, we first approached editing the dae file with
blender, but switched to editing the given dae files after receiving feedback from our
milestone. The most difficult part in this project is that despite our modifications in the
parse_material method in collada.cpp and the dae file our pathtracer still uses the
EmissionBSDF and DiffuseBSDF. We first suspected that we were making mistakes in
the dae file and the collada.cpp such as not passing in parameters correctly. But we
checked the project step by step by inserting print statements and found that the issue
might be somewhere between the parse_material function and the WardBSDF class so
the WardBSDF is not called correctly. We eventually decided to hardcode the
sphere.cpp to take i->bsdf = new WardBSDF((i->n) * 10, 2, 2.5) to skip dae and the
collada.cpp. After we hardcoded the sphere.cpp, we were able to change the material
and color of the spheres to look iridescent. We might still need to work on how to
effectively connect the dae input to the program as future goals.
What we have learned:
We learned about the mathematical and physics knowledge behind the Ward BSDF,
and we also practiced our teamwork skills and debugging skills throughout this project.
For future projects, we would definitely work on better time management and
communication so that we have more time to solve potential problems in the project.

Video Script:
The goal of our project was to render realistic soap bubbles which includes the implementation of
irridescence within our current pathtracer in homework 3. In order to do this we rst intended to
complete the implementation of Wards BRDF within a BSDF class. This would capture the reective
characteristic of soap bubbles making the spheres we are rendering appear shiny and metallic. Here is
our implementation computing the BRDF using two input values for roughness. We then multiplied this
value by a given reectance in order to dene how the light would be reected by the material. After
implementing the BRDF we worked on altering the colors of the spheres in order to mimic irridescence.
Initially, we altered a dae le and respective collada le to use the ward-bsdf when rendering the
spheres within the scene. However, in order to incorporate the color effects we decided to hardcode the
sphere class to use the ward bsdf in order to access the normals at the surface of the spheres. By using
the normals as the reectance vector, we were able to produce iridescent appearing renders that
featured both a reective ring and rainbow shading reminiscent of realistic soap bubbles.
